<li>Dersch , P. , Schmidt , K. , and Bremer , E. ( 1993 ) Synthesis of the Escherichia coli K-12 nucleoid-associated DNA-binding protein H-NS is subjected to growth-phase control and autoregulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17908208" target="_blank">17908208</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS may bind to and directly repress PhilA because repression of hilA in E. coli requires both the upstream repressing sequences and H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11755416" target="_blank">11755416</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS indirectly stimulates flagellar gene expression by repressing hdfR , a known repressor of the flhDC regulatory locus and , in addition , H-NS directly binds to the flagellar protein FliG and helps organize rotor subunit assembly [ 22,74 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375226" target="_blank">25375226</a>]<br></li>
<li>A 2128 bp DNA fragment , encoding hilC and the up-stream gene STM2868 , was digested with DraI and incubated with increasing concentrations of H-NS to test : ( i ) whether the promoter of this gene binds H-NS , and ( ii ) whether this binding is temperature-dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>These two proteins seem to be particularly well matched for the purpose of imposing environmentally-responsive dual control on A+T - rich genes : H-NS binds and silences them while OmpR binds and antagonises H-NS-mediated repression but only when both the OmpR protein and its DNA target are appropriately primed by allosteric control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24603618" target="_blank">24603618</a>]<br></li>
<li>These include the Csp family ( CspA , B , E , G and I ) of RNA-binding proteins with RNA chaperone activity ( Gualerzi , Giuliodori , & Pon , 2003 ) , YmdB , which regulates RNase III activity , and gyrase and H-NS , which negatively supercoil DNA , allowing transcriptional repression ( Kim , Manasherob , & Cohen , 2008 ; Storz & Hengge , 2011 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23651595" target="_blank">23651595</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS confirmed binding sites and transcriptional repression [ 31 ] were compared with our microarray data and Fur repression of hns [ 29 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22017966" target="_blank">22017966</a>]<br></li>
<li>Of the small nucleoid-bind-ing proteins , H-NS and Hha can repress hilA expression , but FIS and HU may activate ( 12 ; citation in references 30 and 47 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107132" target="_blank">12107132</a>]<br></li>
<li>In particular , the abundant nucleoid-associated proteins such as IHF , FIS , HU , and H-NS are known to modulate DNA supercoiling globally and locally ( reviewed in 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12882514" target="_blank">12882514</a>]<br></li>
<li>Numerous transcription factors are involved , including OmpR , MlrA , and CpxR and the nonspeciﬁc DNA-binding proteins H-NS and IHF , in addition to the feed-forward loop involving rpoS and the factors that regulate RpoS activity , including IraP and Crl .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25824832" target="_blank">25824832</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 5B , both the MBP-HilD and H-NS -- FH proteins shifted speciﬁcally DNA fragments 1B , 1C , and 1D but did not shift DNA fragments 1A and 1E or the negative control , sigD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results are in agreement with the in vitro transcription data ( Fig. 7 ) , and suggest that YncC activation and H-NS repression occur independently at pyciGSTM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20713450" target="_blank">20713450</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like Fis , HU , and IHF , H-NS is not thought to-bind any ligand that would alter its activity , and unlike these other proteins , H-NS levels in the cell are relatively constant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15790293" target="_blank">15790293</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it appears that H-NS modulates PhlyE activity both positively and negatively in response to the prevailing growth and/or environmental conditions , such as growth in liquid and on solid media .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
