<li>Addition of SsrB Displaces H-NS When It Is Bound to DNA C in the Polymerized Form and Not the Bridged Form -- In a previous study , we discovered that H-NS has two modes of interacting with DNA and that Mg2 or other divalent cations can switch its binding mode without H-NS being released from DNA ( 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>SsrBC Displaces H-NS from DNA Only When Bound in the Polymerization Mode -- H-NS can switch between polymerization ( i.e. nucleation ) and bridging DNA binding conformations in response to divalent cations ( e.g. Mg2 ) , and we showed that it is the polymerization mode that prevails under physiological conditions ( 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
