<li>It has been reported that StpA can negatively regulate expression of a reporter gene under the control of the hns promoter in E. coli ( Zhang et al. , 1996 ) ; although this could only be observed in the absence of hns , this raised the possibility that StpA-dependent gene expression could simply reﬂect changes in the level of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19843227" target="_blank">19843227</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because of the fact that ompS1 expression in the Salmonella hns mutants did not reach the level attained in the shortened , most active pRO88 fusion , the presence of additional negative effectors aside from H-NS can not be excluded .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14594821" target="_blank">14594821</a>]<br></li>
<li>Quantification of the transcripts showed that the presence of 0.5 mM IHF in the transcription assay did not have a stimulatory effect in the absence of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>]<br></li>
<li>Normalized levels of csgD transcripts were highly up-regulated in the ssrB hns double mutant compared to the ssrB null strain , indicating that the loss of H-NS repression rescued the defect in csgD expression in the absence of SsrB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26880544" target="_blank">26880544</a>]<br></li>
<li>Again , these data are consistent with the proposal that the upstream region determines an appropriate structure for repression , which occurs at high osmolarity in the absence of H-NS or at both low and high osmolarity in the presence of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14594821" target="_blank">14594821</a>]<br></li>
<li>Such curvature could determine a structure needed for repression in the presence of H-NS or at high osmolarity in the hns background .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14594821" target="_blank">14594821</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the BipA GTPase and H-NS do not appear to play a significant role in the regulation of flagellin levels in S. typhimurium , under the conditions tested .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11681212" target="_blank">11681212</a>]<br></li>
<li>As suggested by our previous study ( 14 ) , establishing the Mg2 - responsive regulation of these loci requires the transcriptional-repressor H-NS , which antagonizes the functions of SlyA and PhoP ; thus the mRNA level is reduced greatly in the phoP or slyA mutants in PhoP-activating ( low-Mg2 ) conditions but remains high in PhoP-repressing ( high-Mg2 ) conditions in the hns mutant ( Fig. 4B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19091955" target="_blank">19091955</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the absence of H-NS produced a sixfold increase in levels of - galactosidase under low-osmolarity conditions and a threefold increase in the high-salt medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17675384" target="_blank">17675384</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results are summarized in the diagram depicted in Fig. 7 , where the presence of active Fur ( i.e. , Fur-Fe2 ) results in decrease in [ H-NS ] and increased the expression of hilA ( Fig. 7A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21075923" target="_blank">21075923</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , low levels of assT expression were detected in the absence of P1 and P2 , in a STYhns99 strain , suggesting that the upstream PLeuO promoter activity is also repressed by the H-NS global regulator in N-minimal medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22343301" target="_blank">22343301</a>]<br></li>
<li>The reduction in gene repression brought about by the increase in temperature is concomitant with a conformational change in the protein , resulting in the decrease in size of high-order oligomers and the appearance of increasing concentrations of discrete dimers of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the characterization of the state of the H-NS protein in our mutants , analysis of ompS1 expression in an hns stpA double mutant at both low and high osmolarity , and a search for other negative effectors by mutagenesis in hns mutants are experiments that should help in further deﬁning the mechanism involved in the negative regulation of ompS1 expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14594821" target="_blank">14594821</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nevertheless , when IHF was present at 0.5 mM in the reaction mix , it stimulated transcription twofold in the presence of 1 mM H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , H-NS can repress the activity of the proU promoter in vitro , as it does in vivo at low osmolarity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10766847" target="_blank">10766847</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , elevated K1-glutamate concentrations can overcome the repressive effect of H-NS at the proU promoter in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10766847" target="_blank">10766847</a>]<br></li>
<li>This temperature shift decreases the size of high-order oligomers of H-NS and results in the appearance of dimers which are no longer able to-bind to DNA in a cooperative manner at 37 ° C , resulting in a reduction in gene repression ( Ono et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25080967" target="_blank">25080967</a>]<br></li>
