<li>However , the increase in StpA protein levels in NLM2173 did not allow StpA to substitute for H-NS in the repression of the dsbA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14761985" target="_blank">14761985</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the present study , steady-state levels of H-NS in the wild-type strain were H-NS actually leads to an increase in StpA levels ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14761985" target="_blank">14761985</a>]<br></li>
<li>This behavior has been observed in our single-molecule stretching experiments with H-NS filaments in the presence of SsrB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26880544" target="_blank">26880544</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , in the presence of H-NS , SPI-2 expression is SsrB-dependent , and acid pH is an important inducing signal in vitro for the native SPI-2 promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of H-NS , the requirement for SsrB in activating SPI-2 genes is substantially reduced , suggesting a role for SsrB in countering H-NS silencing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , the SsrB requirement in the absence of H-NS ( see below ) is substantially reduced , suggesting a dual role for SsrB in SPI-2 induction : activation of transcription and countering H-NS-mediated repression ( 238 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>An examination of transcriptional activation during the course of macrophage infection found that all SsrB relieves H-NS silencing of SPI-2 479 SPI-2 operons are activated during growth in vivo in an SsrB-dependent fashion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>The greater effect of SsrB on SPI-2 expression in the presence of H-NS suggests that SsrB plays a role in countering H-NS-mediated silencing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of glucose , H-NS appeared to have a positive effect on hlyE expression ( Fig. 1c ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of glucose , H-NS appeared to have little effect on hlyE expression ( Fig. 1d ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the previous report ( 36 ) , H-NS acted as a strong repressor of hlyE expression , whereas here H-NS appears to have a positive effect on hlyE expression in the absence of glucose but an attenuated or negative effect on hlyE expression in the presence of glucose ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
<li>We next examined the effect of SsrBC addition after H-NS was bound to DNA in the stiffening mode ( Fig. 4E ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>As can be observed , increasing amounts of LeuO modiﬁed the H-NS -- DNA complexes causing a displacement of H-NS from the bound DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17908208" target="_blank">17908208</a>]<br></li>
<li>Such a model would explain why the in vitro DNA binding assays performed with purified components found that Hha can increase the ability of H-NS to-bind DNA under a narrow range of conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 6A , increasing amounts of MBP-HilD shifted the DNA -- H-NS complex to a slower-migrating complex similar to that formed by MBP-HilD ; furthermore , the Western blots indicated that increasing amounts of the DNA-HilD complexes correlate with decreasing amounts of H-NS -- FH bound to the DNA fragments .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>( ii ) Addition of 600 nM SsrB to the H-NS bound csgD DNA resulted in areas of condensation ( pink arrows ; an ` SsrB signature ' ) along with a few areas where the straight H-NS bound conformation persisted ( yellow line ; an ` H-NS signature ' ) ; Scale bar = 200 nm as in Figure 5A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26880544" target="_blank">26880544</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 4 shows that fragments 1 to 5 were retarded in the presence of increasing amounts of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25916986" target="_blank">25916986</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fragment 6 was not retarded in the presence of up to 300 nM H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25916986" target="_blank">25916986</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of the nucleoid-associated protein H-NS on regulation of the LeuO-dependent genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18156266" target="_blank">18156266</a>]<br></li>
<li>Csn-B inhibited the secretion of SPI-1 effectors through the Hha -- H-NS regulatory pathway .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23459474" target="_blank">23459474</a>]<br></li>
<li>The general DNA-binding protein H-NS is required for the full range of repression of the proU operon in media of low osmolality .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7635833" target="_blank">7635833</a>]<br></li>
<li>At higher temperatures , the concentration of dimeric H-NS increases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>Disruption of the Hha/H-NS interaction by the H-NS site-specific mutation I11A results in increased expression of the Hha/H-NS co-regulated gene hilA without affecting the expression levels of proV , a target gene repressed by H-NS in an Hha-independent fashion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , our results revealed that in the absence of the downstream region bound by H-NS or when H-NS is inactivated , the expression of ssrAB becomes independent of HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , we demonstrated that in the absence of H-NS the expression of hilA was independent of Fur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21075923" target="_blank">21075923</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistently , when the activity of H-NS was inactivated , the expression of ssrAB also became independent of HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , they show that in the absence of these negative cis elements , or when H-NS is inactivated , the expression of ssrAB becomes independent of HilD , further supporting the role of HilD as an antagonist of H-NS-mediated repression of ssrAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>To evaluate the effect of H-NS in the regulation of each of the LeuO-regulated genes , individual fusions were transformed into Salmonella serovar Typhi hns mutant STYhns99 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18156266" target="_blank">18156266</a>]<br></li>
<li>Structural response of H-NS to increased temperature To substantiate the observation of the interaction of H-NS being directly affected by temperature , a biophysical investigation of the thermal behaviour of the protein in vitro was performed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the set of genes under control of StpA shares significant overlap with the set of genes regulated by H-NS , in the absence of H-NS , the silencing activity of StpA alone does not provide sufficient repression of H-NS regulated loci [ 46,48,75 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375226" target="_blank">25375226</a>]<br></li>
<li>A study of the hdeAB promoter region suggested H-NS repression was overcome by the RNAPNsS complex , while RNAP associated with the house keeping sigma factor s was more effectively inhibited by the D presence of H-NS [ 85 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375226" target="_blank">25375226</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the strong silencing effect conferred by the DSR was still apparent in the absence of H-NS or Hh Figure 3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16443238" target="_blank">16443238</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of Hha had a lesser effect on silencing by the DSR than did H-NS , which is in contrast to the effect of Hha when the USR was also present .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16443238" target="_blank">16443238</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of low temperature on the regulation of the plasmid-encoded hns gene R27 and the related pSf-R27 plasmid encode a protein related to the global modulator H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24024872" target="_blank">24024872</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , all the fusions tested were derepressed to different degrees in the absence of H-NS and/or Hha ; however , the greatest difference was seen for the effect on the rtsA-lac fusion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17675384" target="_blank">17675384</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under low-osmolarity conditions , the up-regulation of rtsA transcription in the absence of Hha and H-NS was evident , similar to the data obtained with the rtsA-lac fusion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17675384" target="_blank">17675384</a>]<br></li>
<li>This could occur by modulation of the oligomeric state of H-NS which would affect the co-operativity of binding to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the DNA supercoiling was relaxed by repression of H-NS during the passage through mice , which led to decreased survival of the organisms under conditions of NaCl exposure .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14726232" target="_blank">14726232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding of H-NS to the intergenic region caused moderate activation of the regulated csgD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14643403" target="_blank">14643403</a>]<br></li>
<li>The right-hand panel ( 37 ◦ C ) shows the effect of the conformational change on one of the H-NS dimers due to increased temperature .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>This implicates the effect of co-operativity derived from the oligo-merization as the source of differential binding of H-NS to the bacterial DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>We attempted to model the effect of the potential co-operative effect of the binding of H-NS to DNA using various methods , but these were largely inadequate in accommodating the binding of one oligomeric species with another ( see the Experimental section ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test the effect of increasing concentrations of IHF on the yield of trans-cripts from the hilA promoter , the concentration of H-NS was fixed at 1 mM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>]<br></li>
<li>To further localize the regulatory sequences required for the repression of ssrAB by H-NS , we analyzed the effect of dominant negative H-NSQ92am on the expression of the different ssrAB-cat fusions in the absence of HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the expression of ssrAB seems to require the coordinated actions of HilD , which antagonizes repression by H-NS , and OmpR , which probably mediates the interaction of the RNA polymerase with the promoter of this operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>As the concentration of Hha in the binding reactions was increased while the concentration of H-NS was held constant , the hilA fragment shifted to a lower mobility protein-DNA complex ( Fig. 7A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>This enhancement was most noticeable when the concentration of H-NS was kept low ( 300 nM ) and the salt component of the binding reactions was increased to 250 mM in order to lessen the DNA binding capability of H-NS ( i.e. we notice no additional effect of Hha under conditions where H-NS has already fully shifted the promoter fragment ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of H-NS , the hilA promoter appears to be highly active , even in the absence of positive regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vivo however , the magnitude of YncC activation was reduced in the absence of H-NS ( Figs. 2D , E ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20713450" target="_blank">20713450</a>]<br></li>
<li>Red circles are the extension of the same DNA in the presence of 600 nM H-NS when the force was gradually reduced .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of 1 M H-NS , retardation of some of the DNA target was observed as a smear in the gel .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
<li>Presumably , the role of methylation of GATC II is to either inhibit or enhance the binding of additional regulatory proteins , such as Lrp or H-NS , which participate in the formation of the active transcriptional complex ( van der Woude et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692151" target="_blank">10692151</a>]<br></li>
<li>We speculate that PhoP plays the role of a classical transcriptional-activator at the STnc1480 promoter , rather than counter-silencer , as the presence of PhoP is required for transcription even in the absence of a functional H-NS protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27564394" target="_blank">27564394</a>]<br></li>
<li>Relating the fact that the stability of the parallel complex strongly depends on the presence of NaCl to the function of H-NS as a salt-dependent regulator , allows for speculation about a possible mechanism for sensing differences in ionic strength by H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22828335" target="_blank">22828335</a>]<br></li>
<li>Perhaps HF-I simply facilitates the unwinding activity of S1 , or HF-I might counteract a negative inﬂuence of a protein that binds to rpoS mRNA ( e.g. , EF-Tu or H-NS ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8682778" target="_blank">8682778</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the major effect of H-NS activation could be located downstream of the csgD transcriptional start site , although no binding site could be assigned to that region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14643403" target="_blank">14643403</a>]<br></li>
