<li>[ 97 ] A. Nandal , C.C.O. Huggins , M.R. Woodhall , J. McHugh , F. Rodrıguez-Quin ̃ones , M.A. Quail , et al. , Induction of the ferritin gene ( ftnA ) of Escherichia coli by Fe ( 2þ ) - Fur is mediated by reversal of H-NS silencing and is RyhB independent , Mol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23040276" target="_blank">23040276</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of the agfD promoter is regulated by RpoS , OmpR , MlrA , CpxR , H-NS , and IHF ( 23 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17079680" target="_blank">17079680</a>]<br></li>
<li>While H-NS usually acts as a negative regulator of gene expression , hlyE is not the only example of a CRP-regulated gene whose expression is positively regulated by H-NS ; for example , expression of both the malT and csiD genes in E. coli is stimulated by H-NS ( 8 , 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
<li>As the intracellular levels of H-NS increase , H-NS II is occupied and hlyE expression is downregulated by promoter occlusion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996792" target="_blank">14996792</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of SPI-2 by PhoP is controversial , but the PhoPPhoQ two-component system activates other genes required Silencing by Displacing H-NS Bound in Polymerization and Directly Activates Transcription * □ Salmonella enterica uses multiple type III secretion systems as virulence determinants to modulate host cell processes such as signaling , membrane trafficking , and cytoskeleton dynamics to promote virulence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>We report the first example of an sRNA , STnc1480 , that is subject to silencing by H-NS and subsequent counter-silencing by PhoP and SlyA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27564394" target="_blank">27564394</a>]<br></li>
<li>Open complex formation at both the proU and the b-lac promoters is similarly inhibited by H-NS and activated by K1-glutamate in an in vitro assay .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10766847" target="_blank">10766847</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , the S. Typhi CRISPR-Cas locus is regulated by LeuO , H-NS and LRP [ 22 , 26 ] , which are involved in pathogenesis [ 27 -- 32 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28270274" target="_blank">28270274</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have thus demonstrated that , in S. Typhi , cas3 is negatively regulated by the global regulatory protein H-NS , which also silences cse1 [ 26 ] and the antisense ascse2-1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28270274" target="_blank">28270274</a>]<br></li>
<li>By surveying the literature , Atlung and Ingmer ( 1 ) determined that H-NS has a larger effect on target gene expression in scenarios where expression is not also mediated by positive transcription factors and noted that any repression by H-NS is virtually eliminated when positive transcription factors are artiﬁcially induced .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14761985" target="_blank">14761985</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggested that , when present in high amounts in E. coli , YncC/McbR counters H-NS mediated-repression at pyciGECO ( Fig. 4B ) by modulating H-NS binding and , ultimately , by counteracting the negative effects of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20713450" target="_blank">20713450</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is remarkable that in E. coli K-12 , regulation of yciGFE by YncC and by H-NS are intimately linked , whereas in Salmonella , YncC directly activates transcription , and thus , activation by YncC is , at least partly , disconnected from the H-NS network .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20713450" target="_blank">20713450</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because H-NS preferentially binds to regions of high A+T content , relaxation-induced promoters are very likely to be H-NS repressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22457642" target="_blank">22457642</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , antagonists can bind to H-NS , disrupting the H-NS multimeric complexes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21570144" target="_blank">21570144</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although less H-NS bound to SPI promoters in the DompR mutant , significantly more H-NS bound to PompR , suggesting that OmpR is an effective H-NS antagonist at its own promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22457642" target="_blank">22457642</a>]<br></li>
<li>This observation is consistent with the two-step mechanism of H-NS silencing in which H-NS ﬁrst binds to high-afﬁnity sites that nucleate cooperative binding , leading to H-NS polymerization onto adjacent DNA regions ( 54 , 55 , 65 , 73 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25916986" target="_blank">25916986</a>]<br></li>
<li>As SlyA is not able to directly activate transcription in vitro , its role appeared to be limited to counteracting the repressive action of H-NS on genes that were recently acquired by horizontal gene transfer ( Perez et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19843227" target="_blank">19843227</a>]<br></li>
<li>SPI-2 expression is therefore predicted to require relief of H-NS repression in order to activate transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is important to note that although H-NS and StpA bind to the same genes , their effect on gene expression is not equivalent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19843227" target="_blank">19843227</a>]<br></li>
<li>As MicA has recently been shown to negatively regulate phoPQ expression in E. coli ( 107 ) , it is tempting to speculate that MicA may be moderating the effects of DsrA-induced H-NS repression ; however , it is currently unclear whether sRNA regulons are sufﬁciently conserved between E. coli and S. enterica to justify this hypothesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23470992" target="_blank">23470992</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data obtained in this work suggest that tpx and STY1978 belong to the repertoire of genes that are positively regulated by H-NS ; however , additional work is necessary to determine if this regulation is direct or if other proteins are involved in this process .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18156266" target="_blank">18156266</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is thus possible that H-NS silences misL and that binding of MarT to the misL promoter region relieves this repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17351045" target="_blank">17351045</a>]<br></li>
<li>The recent evidence that Fur displaces H-NS from regulatory sites of ftnA and not vice versa ( 45 ) indicates that once Fur is activated the cell is committed to countersilencing and repression of H-NS until iron concentrations are reduced enough to inhibit Fur binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21075923" target="_blank">21075923</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , our data demonstrate that HilD effectively displaces H-NS bound to those sites that mediate the repression of ssrAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the role of OmpR-P in autoinduction is to help to counteract repression by H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12080060" target="_blank">12080060</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12068808" target="_blank">12068808</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the autoinduction role of OmpR-P is most likely to overcome H-NS repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12080060" target="_blank">12080060</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12068808" target="_blank">12068808</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of DNA supercoiling on ompR expression The fact that EnvZ-dependent phosphorylation of OmpR is required to induce ompR suggests that acid stress helps OmpR-P to-bind the R2 site and overcome the repressive effect of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12080060" target="_blank">12080060</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12068808" target="_blank">12068808</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is possible that binding of H-NS to the pef regulatory region could directly repress pef expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692151" target="_blank">10692151</a>]<br></li>
<li>The coincidence of these features seems to produce an ideal platform upon which H-NS can repress the very large number of promoters that it is known to regulate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19443540" target="_blank">19443540</a>]<br></li>
<li>Changes to DNA curvature induced by osmolarity or temperature shifts can modify the bridging activity of H-NS at speciﬁc promoters , allowing for transcription to proceed ( Hinton et al. , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29034217" target="_blank">29034217</a>]<br></li>
<li>Central to the repression mechanism is the creation of DNA -- H-NS -- DNA bridges that impede transcription initiation ( Dame et al. , 2005 ; Dorman & Kane , 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19443540" target="_blank">19443540</a>]<br></li>
<li>SsrB relieves H-NS repression of SPI-2 genes It was recently shown that the nucleoid protein H-NS protects against foreign DNA by binding to A/T-rich regions of DNA ( Lucchini et al. , 2006 ; Navarre et al. , 2006 ) , including SPI-2 , resulting in the inhibition of transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , when IHF was prebound to DNA , addition of increasing amounts of H-NS did not alter the mobility of protein -- DNA complexes ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , 10 mM Mg2 promoted H-NS bridging of DNA , and this DNA binding conformation was insensitive to the presence of SsrB ( Fig. 4F ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>The overexpression of H-NS repressed SPI-2 gene expression ( comparing `` rpoE hns uninduced '' to `` rpoE hns induced '' ) , however when σE was present , the repression of H-NS on SPI-2 was relieved ( compare `` WT hns induced '' to `` rpoE hns induced '' ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25713562" target="_blank">25713562</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , some of these H-NS binding sites may be unproductive for the repression of ssrAB , or another regulator may act along with HilD to counteract a double mechanism of H-NS-mediated repression of ssrAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25135218" target="_blank">25135218</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , countersilencing of H-NS repression appears to be a common aspect of its regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21075923" target="_blank">21075923</a>]<br></li>
<li>As SsrBC is increased to 200 nM , counter-silencing of 200 nM H-NS increases to 5-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using this model , the KD for DNA binding to H-NS increases from approx .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this experiment , H-NS was allowed to-bind to DNA prior to the addition of SsrBC as described under `` Experimental Procedures .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of 600 nM H-NS ( bound to DNA in stiffening mode ) , addition of 300 nM SsrBC leads to DNA folding ( red circles ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , when H-NS is bound to DNA in the bridging mode , it appears to be inert to addition of SsrBC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21059643" target="_blank">21059643</a>]<br></li>
<li>One protein to consider is H-NS , which regulates about 400 genes in Salmonella ( Dame , 2005 ; Dame et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17850262" target="_blank">17850262</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS binds DNA with high A/T content and is believed to regulate horizontally transferred DNA ( Navarre et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17850262" target="_blank">17850262</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we report that this phenotypic difference is mainly dependent on topological changes regulated by H-NS , a bacterial histone-like nucleoid protein that binds non-speciﬁcally to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14726232" target="_blank">14726232</a>]<br></li>
<li>This observation could mean that LeuO binds to DNA differently when it displaces the H-NS protein to turn on a gene than when it binds to impede transcription initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS preferentially binds to intrinsically bent DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22256797" target="_blank">22256797</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , under LPM 20 h condition , H-NS functions to repress SPI-2 gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25713562" target="_blank">25713562</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS resembles TlpA in its ability to repress promoter activity at low temperature ( 34 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11370771" target="_blank">11370771</a>]<br></li>
<li>The small nucleoid-bind-ing protein H-NS represses hilA in response to low osmolarity ( 84 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19074398" target="_blank">19074398</a>]<br></li>
