<li>However , the observation that E. coli YdgT ( 47 ) , Hha ( 22 , 48 ) , and Yersinia YmoA ( 22 ) can bind to the N-terminal oligomerization domain of H-NS suggests that regulatory specificity might be achieved through interaction with accessory proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16301528" target="_blank">16301528</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hha is known to interact with the N-ter-minal dimerization domain of H-NS ; however , the manner in which this interaction enhances transcriptional silencing is not understood .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>We performed a molecular-dynamics study of the H-NS dimerization domain , showing that the parallel complex is sensitive to changes in salt conditions : it is unstable in absence of NaCl , but stable at physiological salt concentrations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22828335" target="_blank">22828335</a>]<br></li>
<li>The three amino acids glycine , serine and histidine remain N-terminal to the H-NS C21S protein after cleavage of the His - tag .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20383013" target="_blank">20383013</a>]<br></li>
