			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">H-NS evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>This protein , sometimes called VicH , is approximately 50 % identical in amino acid sequence to H-NS from Escheri-chia coli ( Tendeng et al. , 2000 ; Cerdan et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28631437" target="_blank">28631437</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS family members function coordinately in an opportunistic pathogen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25916986" target="_blank">25916986</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="EVO_collapse_similarity" for="evo_similarity_3">
Castang , S. , McManus , H. R. , Turner , K. H. , and Dove , S. L. ( 2008 ) H-NS family members function coordinately in an opportunistic pathogen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></label>
<input id="evo_similarity_3", type="checkbox">
<div class="EVO_similar">
<li>Castang , S. , McManus , H.R. , Turner , K.H. , and Dove , S.L. ( 2008 ) H-NS family members function coordinately in an opportunistic pathogen .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19843227" target="_blank">19843227</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>StpA shares 53 % sequence identity with H-NS as well as several functional properties , such as the ability to self-associate and bind AT-rich DNA [ 44 -- 48 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375226" target="_blank">25375226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary LeuO is a quiescent LysR-type regulator belonging to the H-NS regulon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24354910" target="_blank">24354910</a>]<br></li>
<li>The six fragments were radiolabeled and subjected to electrophoretic mobility shift assays using puriﬁed E. coli H-NS ( which shares 98 % similarity and identical DNA-binding sites with the S. Typhimurium H-NS protein ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25916986" target="_blank">25916986</a>]<br></li>
<li>The StpA and H-NS proteins are closely related and share 52 % identity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19843227" target="_blank">19843227</a>]<br></li>
<li>The S. enterica Typhimurium LT2 and E. coli H-NS proteins share 95 % identity and 98 % similarity at the protein level .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25916986" target="_blank">25916986</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="EVO_collapse_similarity" for="evo_similarity_10">
Tendeng , C. , and Bertin , P.N. ( 2003 ) H-NS in gram-negative bacteria : a family of multifaceted proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17908208" target="_blank">17908208</a>]<br></label>
<input id="evo_similarity_10", type="checkbox">
<div class="EVO_similar">
<li>Tendeng C , Bertin PN ( 2003 ) H-NS in Gram-negative bacteria : A family of multifaceted proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16933988" target="_blank">16933988</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS in Gram-negative bacteria : a family of multifaceted proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17981960" target="_blank">17981960</a>]<br></li></div>
				<label class="EVO_collapse_similarity" for="evo_similarity_13">
Nieto , J. M. , Madrid , C. , Miquelay , E. , Parra , J. L. , Rodrıguez , S. , and Juárez , A. ( 2002 ) Evidence for direct protein-protein interaction between members of the enterobacterial Hha/YmoA and H-NS families of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></label>
<input id="evo_similarity_13", type="checkbox">
<div class="EVO_similar">
<li>Nieto , J.M. , Madrid , C. , Miquelay , E. , Parra , J.L. , Rodriguez , S. , and Juarez , A. ( 2002 ) Evidence for direct protein -- protein interaction between members of the enterobacterial Hha/YmoA and H-NS families of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19843227" target="_blank">19843227</a>]<br></li>
<li>Evidence for direct protein-protei interaction between members of the enterobacterial Hha / YmoA and H-NS families of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15790293" target="_blank">15790293</a>]<br></li>
<li>Evidence for direct protein -- protein interaction between members of the enterobacterial Hha/YmoA and H-NS families of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15256548" target="_blank">15256548</a>]<br></li>
<li>Evidence for direct protein-protein interaction between members of the enterobacterial Hha/YmoA and H-NS families of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17307861" target="_blank">17307861</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18039769" target="_blank">18039769</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The ability to interact with H-NS is conserved among other Hha family members , including YdgT and the Hha ortholog from Yersinia enterolitica , YmoA ( 26 , 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>SsrB , a member of the NarL protein family , activates transcription by displacing H-NS but does not appear able to break H-NS bridges [ 44 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22457642" target="_blank">22457642</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the R27 genes belonging to the second compartment , which includes mostly horizontally acquired genes , require a helper protein of the Hha family for their complete silencing by chromosomal H-NS , and can also be modulated by plasmidic H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19521501" target="_blank">19521501</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of the AraC-like protein family , which includes HilC and HilD , have a well-documented ability to displace H-NS [ 45 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22457642" target="_blank">22457642</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of the H-NS protein family are distributed between the alpha , beta and gamma proteobacteria .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375226" target="_blank">25375226</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS belongs to a family of small , abundant , nucleoid-associated proteins of gram-nega-tive bacteria that have the ability to bind DNA , and it has been shown to act as a transcriptional repressor ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19506059" target="_blank">19506059</a>]<br></li>
<li>At many loci , H-NS alone is insufficient for full transcriptional silencing , and members of the Hha/YdgT family of co-regulatory proteins are also required ( 20 , 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23515315" target="_blank">23515315</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Hha protein is a member of a family of small nucleoid-associated histone-like proteins that include H-NS , HU1 , HU2 , and YmoA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11673432" target="_blank">11673432</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS is also capable to form heterodimers with members of the Hha/YmoA family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26441883" target="_blank">26441883</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that H-NS interacts with members of the Hha/YmoA family to specifically silence HGT but not core genome genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19521501" target="_blank">19521501</a>]<br></li>
<li>MarT is a member of the family of ToxR-like regulatory proteins , which are involved in the activation of genes repressed by the histone-like nucleoid structuring ( H-NS ) protein [ 12 ] , and silences genes with GC contents lower than the genomic average by restricting the access of RNA polymerases to the DNA [ 27 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20195364" target="_blank">20195364</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several lines of evidence have shown that proteins belonging to the Hha family interact with members of the H-NS family to modulate gene expression ( 13 , 16 , 17 , 31 , 32 , 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18039769" target="_blank">18039769</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of this family display the ability to use the H-NS protein to silence HGT regions with the help of co-repressors of the Hha family of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19521501" target="_blank">19521501</a>]<br></li>
<li>The novel Hha/YmoA family of nucleoid-associated proteins : use of structural mimicry to modulate the activity of the H-NS family of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26441883" target="_blank">26441883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , members of other transcriptional regulators families such as VirF ( AraC/XilS ) , RovA ( SlyA/Hor ) , and Ler ( H-NS/StpA ) have been described as antagonists of H-NS mainly on genes involved in virulence ( 72 -- 74 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25566242" target="_blank">25566242</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , members of several families of transcriptional regulators have been described as antagonists of H-NS : VirF ( AraC/XylS family ) ( Tobe et al. , 1993 ) , RovA ( SlyA/Hor ) ( Heroven et al. , 2004 ) and Ler ( H-NS/StpA ) ( Bustamante et al. , 2001 ) , among others .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17908208" target="_blank">17908208</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because of the high level of amino acid sequence identity between H-NS and StpA ( 58 % ) , it has been proposed that StpA is a molecular back-up for H-NS ( Shi and Bennett , 1994 ; Sondén and Uhlin , 1996 ; Zhang et al. , 1996 ; Sonnenﬁeld et al. , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17908208" target="_blank">17908208</a>]<br></li>
<li>StpA is a paralogue of H-NS that shows 52 % identity at the amino acid level and has a DNA-binding afﬁnity that is comparable to that of H-NS ( 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14761985" target="_blank">14761985</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given that RstA ( STM1475 ) is a member of the OmpR family of response regulators , it may not be surprising that H-NS regulation is iron dependent and indicates that H-NS may reduce ferrous iron acquisition and transport , thereby reducing Fur activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21075923" target="_blank">21075923</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
