<li>The function of nucleoid-associated proteins , such as H-NS , remains elusive despite extensive efforts towards understanding their physiological role .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14594821" target="_blank">14594821</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , we reaffirmed our earlier observations that H-NS repressed expression of csgD by filament formation , leading to transcriptional silencing ( Figure 4D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26880544" target="_blank">26880544</a>]<br></li>
<li>Base composition was conﬁrmed to play an important role for H-NS as a repressor of gene-expression , because AT-rich genes were 20 times more likely to be repressed by H-NS than GC-rich genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16933988" target="_blank">16933988</a>]<br></li>
<li>While H-NS has been reported to act as a repressor for a wide range of genes , H-NS mediated repressions have been shown to be counter-acted by different regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24079299" target="_blank">24079299</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS commonly behaves as a negative regulator of these genes [ 9 -- 13 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15966862" target="_blank">15966862</a>]<br></li>
<li>When acting as a repressor it has been suggested to function as a backup for H-NS ; nevertheless in several cases LeuO acts as a derepressor of gene-expression by displacement or prevention of H-NS repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25566242" target="_blank">25566242</a>]<br></li>
<li>An example concerns H-NS , identiﬁed here as a repressor of mating as previously shown for F ( 61 ) but described instead as an activator of mating functions in pRK100 ( 54 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16077115" target="_blank">16077115</a>]<br></li>
<li>In E. coli , RcsB regulates together with the auxiliary proteins GadE and BglJ acid stress resistance and the global regulators H-NS , LeuO and CRP , respectively , ( Castanie-Cornet et al. , 2010 ; Salscheider et al. , 2014 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27206164" target="_blank">27206164</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Histone like Nucleoid Structuring protein H-NS is involved in silencing many of the SPI-2 regulon genes in accordance with its role in binding to xenogenic AT-rich sequences and repressing their expression ( Walthers et al. , 2007 ; Navarre et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26880544" target="_blank">26880544</a>]<br></li>
<li>The histone-like nucleoid-structuring protein ( H-NS ) is a major component of protein-mediated chromatin condensation and functions as a global regulator of transcription in enteric bacteria ( Dorman , 2004 ; Rimsky , 2004 ) , playing an important role in regulating gene-expression in response to environmental stresses such as temperature change ( Ono et al. , 2005 ; White-Ziegler & Davis , 2009 ) , osmotic stress , pH change and oxygen availability ( Hommais et al. , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20383013" target="_blank">20383013</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fur also positively regulates other HilA-dependent genes ( invF and sipC ) involved in invasion , by repressing the expression of H-NS ( Troxell et al. , 2011 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Formation of YmoA-H-NS complexes has been shown to modulate expression of invasion and several other H-NS-dependent virulence genes in Yersinia ( Ellison et al. , 2003 ; Heroven et al. , 2007 ) and in Salmonella .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26441883" target="_blank">26441883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recently , a role for the nucleoid-structuring protein H-NS in silencing gene-expression of horizontally acquired genes such as SPI-1 and SPI-2 was elucidated ( Lucchini et al. , 2006 ; Navarre et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17630976" target="_blank">17630976</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , because Fis is involved in the transcriptional regulation of other nucleoid-binding proteins such as HU ( Claret and RouvieÁre-Yaniv , 1996 ) and H-NS ( Falconi et al. , 1996 ) , as well as gyrase ( Schneider et al. , 1999 ) and topoisomerase I ( Weinstein-Fischer et al. , 2000 ) , its contribution to SPI-1 gene regulation could be through altering the expression of these genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11123690" target="_blank">11123690</a>]<br></li>
<li>The nucleoid-associated protein H-NS is a well-characterized example of a modulator that influences gene-expression in response to environmental stimuli such as osmolarity , pH and temperature ( Hulton et al. , 1990 ; Hommais et al. , 2001 ; Ono et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21680637" target="_blank">21680637</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is an open access article under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution License , which permits use , distribution and reproduction in any medium , provided the original work is properly cited Transcription silencing by the H-NS nucleoid-associ-ated protein is a common feature of virulence genes in enteric pathogens ( Porter and Dorman , 1994 ; Hromockyj et al. , 2002 ; Beloin and Dorman , 2003 ; Lucchini et al. , 2006 ; Ba ~ os et al. , 2008 ; Zwir et al. , 2014 ; Dorman , 2015 ; Hu $ ttener et al. , 2015 ; Prieto et al. , 2016 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28631437" target="_blank">28631437</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS is known to repress the transcription of many ﬁmbriae ( Corcoran & Dorman , 2009 ; Korea et al. , 2010 ; Müller et al. , 2006 ; Nicholson & Low , 2000 ; Torres et al. , 2007 ; White-Ziegler et al. , 2000 ) in E. coli and Salmonella , including the Tcf homologue CS1 ﬁmbriae ( Murphree et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26944792" target="_blank">26944792</a>]<br></li>
<li>These included the cold-shock-responsive hns gene previously shown to be activated by Fis ( Dersch et al. , 1994 ; Falconi et al. , 1996 ) , the hha gene whose product can form heteromeric complexes with H-NS and ( like H-NS ) regulates several virulence genes in response to temperature ( Madrid et al. , 2002 ; Nieto et al. , 2002 ) , and the stpA gene that encodes a paralogue of H-NS and can also form heteromers with it ( Deighan et al. , 2003 ; Free et al. , 2001 ; Johansson et al. , 2001 ; Williams et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15256548" target="_blank">15256548</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , nucleoid-associated proteins such as Fis , H-NS , HU and IHF inﬂuence the expression of these virulence genes ( Schechter et al. , 2003 ; Kelly et al. , 2004 ; Mangan et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16999831" target="_blank">16999831</a>]<br></li>
<li>E COUNTERS THE SILENCING OF H-NS ON SPI-2 GENE EXPRESSION Several regulators ( e.g. , σS , SsrB and SlyA ) have been shown to be capable of relieving H-NS silencing of transcription ( Mujacic and Baneyx , 2006 ; Perez et al. , 2008 ; Walthers et al. , 2011 ; Galagan et al. , 2013 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25713562" target="_blank">25713562</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , H-NS , a known repressor of SPI-2 genes ( Walthers et al. , 2007 ) , was also known to regulate the expression of csgD in E. coli and S. Typhimurium ( Ogasawara et al. , 2010 ; Gerstel et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26880544" target="_blank">26880544</a>]<br></li>
<li>LeuO is an H-NS antagonist that regulates positively genes that contribute to bile and acid resistance in V. cholerae ( Ante et al. , 2015a , b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28631437" target="_blank">28631437</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS is a general transcription silencer that represses a large number of genes in Gramnegative bacteria ( Stoebel et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19763423" target="_blank">19763423</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result demonstrates a preference of H-NS to repress genes that are either nGCO or that have no homologs in closely related species .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20003346" target="_blank">20003346</a>]<br></li>
